<article>
    <h1>JUNE 22, 1986</h1>
    <h2></h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201127/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-27"><time>2020-11-27</time></a>
        - <span>SPORT</span>
        - <span role="byline">AGENCE FRANCE-PRESSE</span>
    </section>

    <p>Scored his two leg­endary goals against Eng­land in the World Cup quar­ter-fi­nal in Mex­ico, the “Hand of God” and then his stun­ning high-speed slalom that was later named “Goal of the Cen­tury” (right) by Fifa. Ar­gentina went on to win the tro­phy, beat­ing West Ger­many 3-2 in the fi­nal for their sec­ond ti­tle.</p>
    <p>JUNE 25, 1994</p>
    <p>Skip­pered Ar­gentina to a 2-1 win over Nige­ria at the World Cup in the United States. Af­ter the match he tested pos­i­tive for ephedrine and was sus­pended for 15 months. He had al­ready been banned for 15 months for co­caine use in his Napoli days. Maradona re­tired from play­ing in 1997 and con­tin­ued to strug­gle with drug and wider health prob­lems.</p>
    <p>NOV 4, 2008</p>
    <p>Be­came coach of Ar­gentina, leading them to the 2010 World Cup in South Africa. Elim­i­nated in the quar­ter-fi­nals by Ger­many, he de­parted af­ter the tour­na­ment.</p>
    <p>JUNE 12, 1998</p>
    <p>Given a sus­pended jail sen­tence of two years 10 months for shoot­ing into a group of jour­nal­ists and in­jur­ing sev­eral with an air ri­fle four years ear­lier.</p>
    <p>JULY 8, 1990</p>
    <p>Cap­tained Ar­gentina to a 1-0 de­feat by West Ger­many in the World Cup fi­nal in Rome.</p>
    <p>DEC 11, 2000</p>
    <p>The Fifa Player of the Cen­tury award to hon­our the best player of the past 100 years ended up be­ing a joint award for Maradona and Brazil­ian three-time World Cup win­ner Pele.</p>
    <p>JUNE, 2018</p>
    <p>Maradona at­tracted plenty of at­ten­tion at the World Cup in Rus­sia, in­clud­ing manic goal cel­e­bra­tions and rude ges­tures. He even needed med­i­cal treat­ment af­ter ap­pear­ing to col­lapse at one game.</p>

